docs.lead_paragraph: Mrs. Lydia Sayer Hasbrouck, who publishes the Sybil, a "Dress-Reform" periodical, at Middletown, N. V., is discussing the question whether a married woman should relinquish maiden name. She says that she and her husband agreed to give her name the preference--but she doesn't "care so much as the wave of straw" whether she is called Sayer or Sayer Hasbrouck.

docs.lead_paragraph: FLORENCE NIGHTINGALE--HER HEALTH.--The following communication, addressed to Mr. ARCHIBALD, H. B. M.'S Consul at this port, has been recently received: ROSLIN HOUSE, GREAT MALVERN, Oct. 4, 1858. SIR: Though several months have elapsed since the date of your kind communication to my niece, Miss FLORENCE NIGHTINGALE, it is not very many days since it reached her hands.
